title: For Sale/Trade:  Saiga-12 Quad Rail Conversion
postcontent:
I've thought about it, and I don't really enjoy this gun as much as I should. It's been converted using a G2 single-hook FCG, Tromix trigger guard, and nylon hole plugs. Has a matching Tapco SAW grip and 6-position collapsable M4-style stock in tan (they call it FDE, but that's a steaming load). Has a UTG quad rail forend, which is heavy but rock solid. Also included are the original factory 5rd. box mag, a single MD-20 drum with clear cover, 5rds. of slug and 150rds. of bird in an ammo can, and a two-point QD sling with HK clips. Also, it has a YHM Phantom bracher brake threaded on the original muzzle threads, and I will also include the original thread protector if you want to take it off.

The gun has had 25rds. of walmart slug, 100rds. of #7.5 bird, and 25rds. of Sellier&Bellot 12-pellet buck through it, all functioned fine. The S&B shells are too long for the drum, so I sold the rest away long ago, be aware that roll-crimped ammo will only fit in the box magaqzine.

I value the gun at about $1200-1500, and I'm looking to trade for a nice pistol or bullpup. All bullpups that I am aware of are similar in value and very interesting to me - PS90, FS2000, RFB, MSAR...Pistol-wise I'm looking for a FiveseveN, HK pistols (Particularly the USP in .45 or P7 and P9S models, but am interested in anything HK), or a Desert Eagle just for shits and giggles. I'll consider anything that's close in value, but I've decided that I want to basically collect "fun-gun" pistols and bullpups only, so that's where my focus is shifting. Will also take trade plus cash for lesser-valued guns.

I will only trade FTF in WA state, don't want to bother with shipping as none of my nearby shops are willing to accept transfers. I live in Bremerton and am willing to travel several hours if necessary to meet.

Project gun I finished last year and took to the range once.
Older model Mossberg 500A 12 guage.
New 20" cylinder bore barrel, new 7 shot mag tube, new magtube spring and follower too. Less than 100 rounds down the new tubes.

Here's the cool part about this gun - I chemically stripped the aluminum reciever down to bare metal and began sanding. 600 grit, 1000 grit, 1500 grit, and finally 2000 grit wet/dry paper.
2 hours on the buffing wheel and this thing is clean enough to shave it.

title: For Trade:  Wicked Lasers Spyder Arctic III 1 Watt blue laser. Burns/Cuts/Melts
postcontent:
This is a brand new Wicked Lasers Spyder III Arctic 1 watt blue laser. Right off the bat, I'll tell you that you can go on to Wicked Laser's website right now and order this very laser for $299.99. However, I won't take anything close to that. The FDA (yes FDA) has put an import ban on any handheld laser above 5mw. This particular laser is 200x more powerful then what current import allows. Actually getting your hands on one of these is VERY diffcult. I'm a GM for UPS and even with my connections in customs, it still took me 6 1/2 months to get a hold of mine. From what I'm told 85% of these are seized.

However, once you DO have one, they are pretty incredible. It will burn or melt most things dark colored. You can cut through plastics, light cigs, pop ballons, start fires, etc. The beam is so powerful that if you pointed it straight up in the air, no only can you see the beam the entire way up, but the only reason it doesn't hit outter space is because our inner atmosphere diffuses the beam. If you were at sea, and pointed the beam straight out infront of you, the only reason you aren't able to see it past a certain point is because of the curvature of the Earth.

I understand this isn't what you typically see, so if you have any questions feel free to ask.
